# Split-Licence Declaration

This repository uses a split licence following the T(h)reehouse +EC corporate
design blueprint §0.3 (split licence architecture). Different parts of the
repository are released under different licences, mirroring the Harbour's
own epistemic architecture: Coastlines (frameworks) are open infrastructure;
Sails (interpretive works) are protected authorial output; Handbook assets
are maximally integrable code/design under MIT.

## Licence matrix

| Layer | Folder(s) | Licence | SPDX | Full text |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Core frameworks (Coastline) | `coastlines/`, `ledger/`, `views/`, `docs/`, `workplans/` | CC BY-SA 4.0 | `CC-BY-SA-4.0` | [`LICENSE-CC-BY-SA-4.0`](LICENSE-CC-BY-SA-4.0) |
| Authored works (Sail) | `sails/` | CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 | `CC-BY-NC-SA-4.0` | [`LICENSE-CC-BY-NC-SA-4.0`](LICENSE-CC-BY-NC-SA-4.0) |
| Design assets (Handbook) | `assets/` | MIT | `MIT` | [`assets/LICENCE`](assets/LICENCE) |
| Code and tooling (Infrastructure) | `numerics/`, scripts, configuration | MIT | `MIT` | [`LICENSE-MIT`](LICENSE-MIT) |
| Fonts (external) | (not redistributed; canonical Google Fonts URL is referenced) | SIL OFL 1.1 | `OFL-1.1` | upstream |

The repository's content layers and their licences are:

- **`coastlines/`** — versioned framework notes (CC BY-SA 4.0).
- **`ledger/`** — Breakwater Claim Analysis Ledger entries (CC BY-SA 4.0).
- **`views/`** — presentational vantage-points; Harbour Views (CC BY-SA 4.0).
- **`sails/`** — commentaries and authored essays (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0).
- **`docs/`** — tutorial, roadmap, project logbook, literature-review plan, methodological notes, Views-category specification, pilot-reader brief (CC BY-SA 4.0).
- **`workplans/`** — planning artefacts including the toolkit work plan and D6-locked API contracts (CC BY-SA 4.0).
- **`numerics/`** — `tmc-numerics` Python toolkit: code, tests, example notebooks, committed JSON results (MIT — see [`numerics/pyproject.toml`](numerics/pyproject.toml)).
- **`assets/`** — design assets (emblem, wordmark, `tokens.css`) copied from `threehouse-plus-ec/cd-rules` per blueprint §0.10 Model B (MIT — see [`assets/LICENCE`](assets/LICENCE) and [`assets/SOURCE.md`](assets/SOURCE.md)).

## How to cite

Citations of documents in this repository must include the version number of
the specific document (e.g. *Coastline v0.4*, *CL-2026-006 v0.5.1*, *Sail v0.4*,
*Harbour View v0.1*). The repository as a whole is archived at a persistent
Zenodo DOI; see [`README.md`](README.md) and [`CITATION.cff`](CITATION.cff).

## Why a split, not a single licence?

A uniform NC-SA licence would create licence islands that cannot interoperate
with the open-source ecosystems this project touches (QuTiP, NumPy, SciPy,
GitHub-native workflows, ARTIQ/Sinara, reproducible-research tooling). The
NC clause introduces legal ambiguity for universities, spin-offs, and
mixed-funding organisations, producing a chilling effect even when use is
benign. The split architecture resolves this:

- For Coastlines and design assets, authority flows from use and citation
  (matching the project's epistemology); both are maximally reusable.
- For Sails (authored essays), authority flows from both use and licence
  restriction (matching the nature of interpretive output); NC protects
  authored prose from commercial repackaging without the epistemic
  commitments that give it meaning.
- For the numerical toolkit (`numerics/`), MIT licensing maximises
  integrability with computational research workflows.

See the corporate design blueprint at
[`threehouse-plus-ec/cd-rules`](https://github.com/threehouse-plus-ec/cd-rules)
§0.3 for the full rationale and the per-folder licence-declaration discipline
this repository follows.

## Per-folder LICENCE references

When in doubt about which licence applies to a particular file:
1. Check the folder it lives in against the matrix above.
2. If the folder has its own `LICENCE` file (as `assets/` does), that file governs.
3. If a file carries its own licence header (as `assets/tokens.css` does), that header governs.
4. When folders contain mixed content, the more restrictive licence applies unless individual files carry their own header declarations.

## Relicensing

The repository steward may relicense specific files to a more permissive
licence (e.g. CC BY-SA to CC BY, or MIT to CC0) but never to a more
restrictive one. Relicensing from Sail (NC-SA) to a permissive licence
requires explicit steward decision and is recorded in the relevant document's
version history.
